wp:term.wp:term_description: Foma is an old school Czech firm which specialises in old school papers and films. It's production processes are pretty much the same as when they were producing film back in the 30's! This is a good brand for those seeking a more old school look, and great for those wanting to do things in bulk - Foma is generally cheap!

Fujifilm are generally the don's when it comes to colour film. Ranging from the basic to the professional, Fujifilm will not let you down when it comes to smoothness, rich colours, and of course the fabled Velvia!

Ilford specialize in making excellent quality silver based black and white photographic materials. Rigorous quality checks mean the film is a little pricier but it'll never let you down. This is the brand for you if you want good results with minimum effort!

Known for the corny catchphrase 'the Kodak moment' this brand is better known for producing some famous cameras, and film since time began! Its colour film tends to be more expensive than Fuji, but it's quality is backed up by photojournalists, and National Geographic photographers alike!

Rollei are an old German photographic firm who specialise in building some of the most expensive cameras ever! Yes the famous Rolleiflex comes from here, and if you own one - well you should probably treat it to more expensive film! Yes Rollei generally sell cheap film, but it's durable stuff, and much recommended for general purpose.

item.title: Stock
item.dc:creator: syw07
item.content:encoded:
For those interested in film photography, experimenting with different film to find a desired effect or quality is both rewarding and important. We stock a range of 35mm and 120 films which will hopefully satisfy the curiosity of our inquisitive members, whilst we also stock more 'typical' films for those who prefer the more reliable types. Hopefully this section will help you decide which film you would like to try out, with useful information about each film type, their price and whether we have it in stock.

Black and White Film

Ilford specialize in making excellent quality silver based black and white photographic materials. Rigorous quality checks mean the film is a little pricier but it'll never let you down. This is the brand for you if you want good results with minimum effort!

HP5+ “The all rounder.”

400 speed general purpose film which has been labelled as bulletproof film! It is hard to develop wrong, it can be u sed in all sorts of lighting conditions and the exposure latitude is huge (it can be underexposed or overexposed by up to 3 stops). This film is perfect if you are new to photography and would like good results with nice fine grain. Price £3.00, £2.50 Status: 35mm and 120 in stock.

Delta 100 “Smoothest tones.”

Professional 100 speed film which excels in fine grain control. The outdoor results are a pleasure to behold, as are the extraordinary sharpness and tonal smoothness. This film is perfect for those shooting outdoor, portraiture where smooth delicate tones are required although try not to push this film (don’t shoot at above 100 speed)! Price: £3.00 Status: 120 in stock

Rollei Retro “Cheap but reliable.”

Comes in 2 speeds: 100 and 400. This film offers excellent value for money, and currently is our cheapest film. Apparently the film has excellent fog penetration, although from my own experience the main draws are its reliability and price. Not as smooth as the Ilford films, and tends to display a little more contrast and grain in the 400 speed variant, but the effect can be quite dramatic. Price: ISO100 £1.50, ISO400 £2.00 Status: 35mm in stock

Fuji Neopan 1600 “Stunning grain structure!”

Perfect for low light outdoor or indoor photography and offers the most beautiful grain structure. The film can be pushed to ISO3600 and is therefore essential for night shoots without a flash. The main draw is the sensational grain which creates a caustic, speckled texture which is a pleasure to the eye. Price: £3.50 Status: 35mm in stock

item.title: Dpreview
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: A great resource for reviews on the latest and greatest digital cameras. They will have reviewed pretty much every digital SLR, and most compacts as well, on the market and the depth of their reviews are staggering! You’ll find everything from full specs to image quality reviews and even ISO comparisons. The first (and usually only) place you need to look to find your new camera.

item.title: Digital Photography School
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: A great place to pick up some good tips on how to take better photographs. They have tutorials ranging from the basic to the more advanced. A great place to start if you want to improve your photography.

item.title: Photo.net
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: A thriving community of photographer with a great forum. Almost every question that you can think of regarding any aspect of photography (and plenty more besides!) has probably been answered on these forums.

item.title: 7DayShop
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: The place to buy film in the UK. They usually have the cheapest prices and the biggest selection on film anywhere and although their delivery can sometimes be quite slow, the prices can’t be beaten! They also stock a wide array of digital accessories at rock bottom prices (memory cards and batteries).

item.title: Small Battery Company
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: As the name suggests they deal with small batteries! Specifically batteries for old film cameras that are hard to find or not made any more. As long as you can find the original battery model the Small Battery Company will suggest alternative batteries that will fit. Truly a life saver if you like film cameras but don’t have the nack for manual metering.

item.title: The Massive Dev Chart
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: A great resource if you can’t find the timings for that film your trying to develop in that obscure developer. It has every film and developer under the sun (and a couple more besides!) and they even have an iPhone app in case you like to check your film timings on the go!

item.title: Transpacolor
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: An online film developing service. Request a film bag on the website and then just post your film (medium format, 35mm, colour and slide) away in the freepost envelope and then wait around a week and you will get lovely developed negatives! Maybe not the quickest developing service around but definitely one of the cheapest and I have never had a problem with the results yet! They also do enlargements and scans.

item.title: Silverprint
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: Our own local film shop. Located near Waterloo station they sell pretty much every film and chemical you would ever want. Great place for any darkroom related material. Have a look through their online catalogue to see what they have in stock. Warning: they are not the cheapest around but if you need some film or chemicals quickly, or just like buying from a real shop not online, then Silverprint it the place to go. Also they do student discounts!

item.title: Fixation
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: Another London based camera shop with a very big rental service and 2nd hand camera shop.

item.title: AG Photographic
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: Sells a wide variety of films including some exotic ones. Not quite as cheap as 7DayShop but if their is a particular film that you are after, or you just want something different, then have a look at their catalogue.

item.title: Flickr
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: A great photo sharing website. We use it a lot to showcase our members work on our group pool and we have our own profile where we upload any communal work like our recent photography exhibition. It’s free to join though you can buy a pro account for ~£20 to get rid of the restrictions on how much you can upload.

Photosoc is here to cater for all your photographic needs. Whether you are student wanting to learn more about how to get the best out of your camera, or you are involved with another club and you are trying to get some great photos of your activities and members. If you want photos taken of an event, or of your club, or of anything for that matter, just drop an e-mail to photographic.society@imperial.ac.uk and we will get back to you to discuss details.

joining photosoc

item.content:encoded:
Photosoc has its own darkroom for use by members. To use it you there is no need to book, just pick up key 16 from Beit security (see map). See the instructions below. If you don't know how to use the darkroom, but want to learn, there are plenty of lessons for beginners. Have a read on the tutorials page, or have a look on the news page for any lessons coming up. It's also important for all users to be familiar with the rules of the darkroom. We don't want to find any people collapsed in the corner from sniffing chemicals!

using the darkroom

When you turn up for darkroom you must sign the logbook in order to obtain the darkroom key (number 16) from the security guard at the entrance to the quad. Members are able to use the chemicals & paper provided, but must note down in the logsheet (in the darkroom, just inside the door) exactly what they use. Members are reminded to check that the lights and water are off, and that the darkroom is in a tidy state before leaving (see the rules).

When you leave, PLEASE remember to put the key back in security - it is incredibly frustrating to come in for a darkroom session only to find that someone has walked off with the key. If you come out of the darkroom late and there is no guard on duty, either phone Sherfield security from the phone next to the security lodge door, or simply post the key through the letterbox of the security lodge.

Photosoc Film

For those interested in film photography, experimenting with different film to find a desired effect or quality is both rewarding and important. We stock a range of 35mm and 120 films which will hopefully satisfy the curiosity of our inquisitive members, whilst we also stock more 'typical' films for those who prefer the more reliable types. Choosing can be tricky, especially if you've never shot with it before and have no idea how grainy or contrasty the film is. This page should help you pick film ideal for the type of photography you are interested in. Along with preview images, description, price, and stock check, just run your cursor over the picture and check out the grain pattern!
Remember, we sell film every Thursday lunchtime between 1-2 in the darkroom.

item.title: Rules
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Here are the rules that we all have to follow when using the darkroom. They are here for everyone's benefit - they may look boring, but please take the time to read and inwardly digest. Remember, getting caught disobeying any of these can lead to your suspension from the society. You have been warned!
  • The darkroom is only for members of the Imperial Photographic Society.
  • To get into the darkroom, show your membership card to Security, then sign the logbook. You are then responsible for all the equipment and you will be given the key.
  • None of the equipment can be removed from the darkroom.
  • You may store your chemicals and paper in the darkroom in the cabinet provided at your own risk. If they are placed in the "Members only" cabinet they might be used by other members of the society. Unlabelled or outdated chemicals will be removed by the Darkroom Manager.
  • Before using any new chemicals you should make sure that you read the instructions and the warnings very carefully.
  • Ask any of the committee members if you are unsure of any of the effects of the chemicals. During the lessons you will be reminded of the safety rules.
  • There is a ventilator in the darkroom which will remove all of the chemical scents to avoid any nausea or other effects.
  • The Darkroom Manager ensures that none of the chemicals in the darkroom are out of date. Any problems with the darkroom can be reported to him.
  • Do not consume the chemicals.
  • You can use special plastic gloves of your own when handling the chemicals. The society provides tongs for the members to use in order to keep their hands dry. There is no need for you to use your hands when developing and printing pictures.
  • There are logsheets where you must fill in what you have used during your time in the darkroom.
  • If something is lost or damaged you are advised to write it in the Darkroom Logbook and to inform Beit Security and a committee member.
  • After you have used the darkroom, you must make sure that the equipment is clean and all the rubbish is in the bin before you leave the darkroom. If the room is messy after you leave, you will be suspended from the darkroom until you have a chat with the Management! If you find the darkroom in a state, you should report it but also clean it up before leaving.
  • Lock up the darkroom when you leave and return the key to Security, and fill in the remaining columns in the logbook.
Chemicals and Paper are free to use for darkroom members, however excessive use may result in a bill for you to pay. If you are printing or developing in any suffcient quantity it is recommended that you purchase and use your own consumeables.

Experiment with slow shutter speeds to show movement in your photographs.

What's on in London

The World Press Photo's annual exhibition is going to be held in the Royal Festival Hall in the South Bank Centre from the 27th of November. Its usually very good and free so I recommend that all of you go and check it out!

item.title: AGM
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
So it's that time of the year again to start picking members for next years committee! If you’re enthusiastic about photography and you're willing to put in a little bit of time to run a society catering for all of us budding photographers, this is your chance! Here is the list of committee positions available and a small description of what they do:

  • Chair: As chair you’ll be in charge of making your vision of what photosoc should be a reality. You'll be the one making the final decisions and making sure that the rest of the committee are doing their jobs. This is the position for you if you feel you can really improve the society.
  • Vice-Chair: This position is also available, if there is more than 1 candidate running for chair. We will then decide who gets which position at the AGM. The vice-chair's job will be to assist the chair in running the society, organising trips and events for our members.
  • Treasurer: The treasurer is one who holds financial responsibility of the club, together with the chair. Your job will be to make sure that the budget is kept in good shape, signing off claim forms. Basically anything to do with money!
  • Secretary: As a secretary, you will be in charge of making sure everything gets done on time, papers are filed, minutes are taken at meetings etc..
  • Darkroom Manager: You will be in charge of looking after the darkroom and organizing darkroom tutorials, so some experience with developing and printing is recommended.
  • Events Coordinator: You will be in charge of the ‘business’ side of photosoc, offering photographic coverage for plays, concerts and dinners for the other societies at Imperial.

If you're interested in taking on any of these roles then put together a quick manifesto of what you plan to do and why you should get the job. Include a photo of yourself and send it to us atphotosoc@ic.ac.uk. Don't worry it doesn't have to be anything elaborate!

We will then be holding an AGM sometime soon for everyone to vote in the new committee but we will let you know more about that nearer the time. If you have any questions about the role you're interested in then please don't hesitate in sending us an email.

The film is made by the Dutch firm: Impossible BV which bought an old Polaroid factory and, through a deal with Ilford, has started producing black and white Polaroid film which is compatible with Polaroid SX-70 and 600 series. There are two types of films being sold: PX600 and PX100 Silver Shade films with ISO's of 600 and 100 respectively and are being sold through the Impossible website at €18 per pack with 8 sheets in each pack. The Photographers Gallery is selling the PX100 film at £19.99 from Saturday. The company has also confirmed that the first two colour films (ISO 100 and 600) will go on sale this summer. item.title: Life Through The Lens: Debauchery, Lenses & Vodka
item.dc:creator: trixy54
item.content:encoded:
Life Through The Lens: Debauchery, Lenses & Vodka By Tristan Brown

It’s ten o’clock on a Saturday night. People of all ages are out around the town. Drinkers are down in the pubs, clubbers out in the clubs, couples were… Well they were out doing whatever it is couples do. Stepping out of the tube station, I am greeted by a group of middle-aged ladies all dressed up raring to go on the prowl. “Hey You!” they shout at me; their tights are a little worse for wear, and their make up is a little shoddy but I’m a forgiving guy, so I greet them anyway. They aren’t particularly attractive and I swear the blonde has some rather excessive hair down her cleavage.

After a couple of minutes, my somewhat misplaced-where-the-sun-don’t-shine brain starts to kick into action: the deep, coarse voices, the diva-tastic hair, the unnecessary extra blusher (blue so didn’t suit her). I sigh. At least I’m in the right place. After a brisk walk through two parks, one friendly neighbourhood, one not so friendly estate and a few alleys, I finally reach the venue. To little surprise, I am greeted by a six foot man dressed from head, and indeed, to foot in a kimono. Of course I am. Complete with a thick and voluptuous wig, had it not been for his massive collar bone or his stubble or perhaps the pointed nose, I would have mistaken him for quite a her. Quite an impressive her. Dear reader, allow me to attempt to enlighten yourselves as to how I managed to get myself into such a situation. I’m a bit of a photographer, I do so enjoy it and I take pleasure in lively subjects. Surfing the web for events to photograph leads me to a myriad of options, naturally. The one event that really caught my eye though, was entitled “the Tranny Olympics.” Intriguing. Always up for new things, I thought why not? Twenty minutes later, after a quick call to the organiser, I was the official photographer for the Tranny Olympics 2009.

Welcome to life as it’s seen through the lens.

The venue was a warm, homely pub that probably would have looked quite regal and amicable during the day. Oh sweet irony, as tonight it would be home for around three hundred of London’s most fine transvestites. As I approach the entrance, the hefty chunk of meat of a bouncer rolls his eyes at me, “Good luck in there.” He says. Interesting. As with any event, I fire a few test shots to try and get a feel of the lighting. Blank; Keep forgetting to take off the lens cap. After having looked around, making sure nobody saw my schoolboy error I removed the cap, plugged in the flash and wandered around. There were some interesting costumes donned by a few of the participants that night. There was Jesus in a traditional white robe and stilettos, a leopard-tutu-donning Santa/Member of Ramstein, a slim Freddy Mercury in hotpants and an eloquent Elton john dressed like a nun.

The opening ceremony was no Beijing, but it did involve copious amounts of vodka, some thongs and lots of glitter; the less said about that the better.

I won't show you what the little Miss Diva (on the left) does next; Apparently it's not fit for imageshack's Terms of Services.

Moving swiftly on, whenever you have a big camera in a small area, people look at you. It’s awkward and sometimes a bit uncomfortable. When people are drunk they lose their inhibitions. It’s awkward and sometimes a bit uncomfortable. But when you have a camera around drunken people, it’s even worse. Every tom, dick and dickhead wants their shot taken, hoping to be seen in tomorrows Metro. Sure, that can be fun, but when its one of those extremely insecure men trying to impress-his mates, it just gets old very fast.

After some on-stage humping, stripping and dancing the highlight of the night is announced, the “Tranny Olympics 100m Sprint.” This sounds promising. The pub starts to clear out onto the streets. I have to say, it is among one of the surrealist situations I’ve found myself in. Imagine for one moment it’s about eleven at night, you are in the middle of a street surrounded by hundreds of transvestites, lining up for a race down an alley. I think it was about now I noticed a young Asian boy carrying a sex doll two sizes too big for himself; mentally, I named him Ernie. Ernie proved to be the most popular man that night, definitely getting all the ladies. And men. Once the race was over, the crowd decided to go on protest. Everybody marched towards the high street, chanting “One, two, three, four! Tranny Rights, we want more!” Bemused drinkers came out of their pubs to view the spectacle and take some photos from their phones. Hrmph. Amateurs.

If you don’t carry an SLR at all times, you ain’t a photographer. From the distance, I spotted somebody else armed with an SLR; as soon as I had spotted their body and lens, I immediately became protective. Any photographer who claims he has never suffered from the hideous ailment known only as lens-envy or lens-lust is a liar. I looked down pitifully at Alyona , giving her a timid pat. She has been with me years, and that’s time no camera can replace.

I digress.

As my night comes to an end, I look back at all the people I had met that night; still drunk off their, by now at least, horribly dreged lipstick, smudged mascara and sweaty-perfumed head. Despite not having anybody I knew tag along with me, I had still had one of those nights in the areole of my lifes most memorable nights. As a photographer. Life through then lens, eh? Not bad. Not bad at all.

item.title: Useful Websites
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Here is a small list of websites that you may find useful for your photography. It will be continually updated so check back for updates and if you have any suggestions then please do contact us.

DPReview

A great resource for  reviews on the latest and greatest digital cameras. They will have reviewed pretty much every digital SLR, and most compacts as well, on the market and the depth of their reviews are staggering! You'll find everything from full specs to image quality reviews and even ISO comparisons. The first (and usually only) place you need to look to find your new camera.

Digital Photography School

A great place to pick up some good tips on how to take better photographs. They have tutorials ranging from the basic to the more advanced. A great place to start if you want to improve your photography.

Photo.net

A thriving community of photographer with a great forum. Almost every question that you can think of regarding any aspect of photography (and plenty more besides!) has probably been answered on these forums.

7DayShop

The place to buy film in the UK. They usually have the cheapest prices and the biggest selection on film anywhere and although their delivery can sometimes be quite slow, the prices can't be beaten!  They also stock a wide array of digital accessories at rock bottom prices (memory cards and batteries).

Small Battery Company

As the name suggests they deal with small batteries! Specifically batteries for old film cameras that are hard to find or not made any more. As long as you can find the original battery model the Small Battery Company will suggest alternative batteries that will fit. Truly a life saver if you like film cameras but don't have the nack for manual metering.

The Massive Dev Chart

A great resource if you can't find the timings for that film your trying to develop in that obscure developer. It has every film and developer under the sun (and a couple more besides!) and they even have an iPhone app in case you like to check your film timings on the go!

Transpacolor

An online film developing service. Request a film bag on the website and then just post your film (medium format, 35mm, colour and slide) away in the freepost envelope and then wait around a week and you will get lovely developed negatives! Maybe not the quickest developing service around but definitely one of the cheapest and I have never had a problem with the results yet! They also do enlargements and scans.

Silverprint

Our own local film shop. Located near Waterloo station they sell pretty much every film and chemical you would ever want. Great place for any darkroom related material. Have a look through their online catalogue to see what they have in stock. Warning: they are not the cheapest around but if you need some film or chemicals quickly, or just like buying from a real shop not online, then Silverprint it the place to go. Also they do student discounts!

Fixation

Another London based camera shop with a very big rental service and 2nd hand camera shop.

AG Photographic

Sells a wide variety of films including some exotic ones. Not quite as cheap as 7DayShop but if their is a particular film that you are after, or you just want something different, then have a look at their catalogue.

Flickr

A great photo sharing website. We use it a lot to showcase our members work on our group pool and we have our own profile where we upload any communal work like our recent photography exhibition. It's free to join though you can buy a pro account for ~£20 to get rid of the restrictions on how much you can upload.

item.title: General Election: Main Parties Issue Photo Rights Pledges
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
I'm sure most of you will be following the election campaign at the moment since its pretty hard to get away from! Anyway I thought I would fill you in on what the three main parties are promising in regard to photographers rights. Here is what they say in no particular order: (taken from Amateur Photographer)

Conservatives

A Conservative government would end police misuse of controversial stop-and search powers that have hit many innocent photographers, Shadow Home Secretary Chris Grayling has said. The pledge follows a call made by Amateur Photographer magazine to Conservative Central Office this morning. In a statement the Conservative Party said: 'Many people, particularly amateur photographers, have said that the Government has allowed the police to misuse counter-terror powers to target innocent tourists and bystanders.' Shadow Home Secretary Chris Grayling added: 'Gordon Brown and Labour have trampled our civil liberties for far too long. Whether they're trying to impose ID cards, or allowing hundreds of thousands of innocent people to be stopped and searched under Terrorism powers, they always seem to think the state knows best. 'We can't go on like this. Conservatives will end the abuse of stop-and-search as part of a full review of all Labour's counter-terrorism laws.'
Amateur Photographer Article

Lib Dems

The Liberal Democrats have called for an 'urgent' review of counter-terrorism stop and search legislation, saying it must not be used to target photographers and tourists. The party told Amateur Photographer (AP) that while it backs the use of police stop and search as an anti-terrorism measure, Section 44 must be reviewed. 'This law is in urgent need of a very big clarification,' a Lib Dem Home Affairs spokesman said. He told us that innocent members of the public, including photographers, have 'fallen foul of this government's attitude towards counter-terrorism legislation'. 'We think that Section 44 has been overused and used for purposes for which it was not intended.' Reacting to figures that show a 66% rise in stop and search Liberal Democrat Shadow Home Secretary Chris Huhne added: 'When trainspotters, photographers and Japanese tourists are all up in arms, it should be clear even to Labour this law needs to be tightened up. 'Random and indiscriminate use of stop and search is an infringement of liberty and alienates the communities we rely on most for the intelligence and witnesses to fight terrorism.'
Amateur Photographer Article

Labour

Asked for the Labour Party's latest stance on this issue, a spokesman told Amateur Photographer (AP): 'We've made clear we want to see police forces only use stops and searches under Section 44 of the Terrorism Act for terrorism-related searches, not for other reasons.' In a meeting with Amateur Photographer magazine staff last month, the government attempted to reassure photographers that they are not being 'targeted' by police officers under anti-terrorism stop and search powers. The government's terrorism watchdog, Lord Carlile, recently confirmed to AP that he has called for Section 44 of the Terrorism Act to be abolished.
Amateur Photographer Article Do you have any thought's on the parties promises? Tell us in the comments.

item.title: Life Through The Lens: Getting Ready For A Job
item.dc:creator: trixy54
item.content:encoded: So as I sit here in my cosy room at eleven thirty at night not a mere fourteen days till exams, it begins to dawn on me that I’m supposed to be taking photos tomorrow evening. Instead of getting ready or at least doing something productive, I decide to finish my episode of Junior Apprentice on iplayer and start writing this. Now the idea goes like this: As I finish writing about a step, I carry out that step and by the end of this both you and I will be ready to go! This way, I’m being doubly as productive. Tristan’s guide to getting ready: Start Time: 11.04pm Step 1) Confirm you still have the job with the organizers or whoever contacted you. Step 2) Put on some pumping music so you can dance whilst you get ready. Step 3) Put your camera battery on charge. A half empty battery is just never acceptable (why yes, I am a pessimist). Step 4) Wipe all your lenses down, no smudges to photoshop out for me please! Step 5) Check, then double check, then triple check and finally quadruple check your dioptre is perfect on the viewfinder. item.title: The Darkroom
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
We are fortunate enough to have a well stocked, fully functional, all rounded darkroom here at Imperial. The darkroom contains all the chemicals, and equipment needed for processing b/w film and prints as well as colour and slide film developing/scanning. For our digital camera users we have a colour calibrated 24 inch monitor and computer with Photoshop CS2 for image editing.

If you would like to use any of these facilities you can purchase a darkroom card which will grant you access to the darkroom located in the West wing basement of Beit quad. It is in here where you will be learning colour developing, slide film printing, cross processing, alternative processes, lith printing, b/w printing and spend whole weekends forgetting what time it is! But lets not get ahead of ourselves, first we need to learn the basics before we can start using the darkroom so you will be required to take a brief orientation in which you will find out where everything goes and how to develop a roll of b/w film. If you have some b/w film laying around please bring it in, as we can use this to demonstrate the process (free developing!) If you are interested in getting a darkroom card please go online and buy the darkroom membership (£10). You can sign up to an induction by using the form on our website. We will run orientations every day over the next week between 1 and 1.45 and will meet in the darkroom (map).

Please note, you will have to become a member of photosoc first (you can find that on the union site too) which is an additional £5 but hey, free chemicals (unlimited) and discounted film prices equals unlimited the opportunity to learn new skills and actually put them into use for free! Wow now there's a good deal!

Hope to see you there,

Sam - Darkroom Manager

item.title: How to Develop Black and White Film
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Tool Preparation

In this lesson we shall be processing a 35mm roll of film using a selected developer. Before we begin it is important to make sure that everything needed is available:-
  • Film Developer (Ilfotec HC, Rodinol, or Xtol)
  • Premixed Stop Bath
  • Premixed Fix (Found in the accordion container)
  • Chamois Cloth or a Squeegee or even your Fingers (to wipe the film)
  • Developing Tank complete with Funnel, Lid and Spindle
  • A dry Film Reel
  • Three Measuring Cylinders marked ‘Developer,’ ‘Stop’ and ‘Fixer’
  • Smaller Measuring Cylinder (for measuring out developer)
  • Jug of Water at 20°C
  • Film Canister Opener or Film Retriever
  • Film Clips (one heavy and one light)
  • Scissors, Film Sleeves

Chemical Preparation

You need three chemicals to process a film, developer, stop and fixer. These should be prepared before you remove the film from its canister.

Developer

Choosing your developer is an important stage in controlling the amount of contrast or grain on your negative. We currently stock 3 developers: Rodinol, more grain, very high sharpness; Ilfotec HC, sharp, high quality smooth tones; Xtol, extra fine grain. Of course grain is also down to the film you have used! Check the concentration and development time of your film by logging onto the members section on the laptop and going to Massive Dev Chart to find your selected film, and selected developer. Depending on the ISO speed of the film, you are given a choice of concentrations and developing times. Select an appropriate combination (between 5-15 mins) Mix the solution by measuring out appropriate amounts of the developer with 20°C water e.g. The processing instructions for Ilford HP5 Plus say that you need a 1+31 concentration of Ilfotec HC developer. Given that the developing tank has a capacity of 300ml, measure out 9.5ml of developer and add it to 290.5ml of 20°C water into a measuring cylinder.

Stop

This is provided already diluted. Just pour out 300ml of it into a measuring cylinder.

Fixer

This is an expensive chemical, so we have provided communal premixed solution in the accordion container stored by the sink.

Loading the Film

This is most difficult stage of processing. Find a dry film reel (otherwise the film will stick) and place it together with a developing tank, funnel, spindle and lid on a table together with a pair of scissors and either a film retriever or film can opener. Using a film retriever is fairly tricky, but makes things easier. The alternative method is to use the film can opener. Switch the lights off, the fan off and lock the door. Cover up and light gaps with the wooden batons and bits of card. Go back to the table and open the film canister. Cut the lip of the film off and feed it into the reel. Once you’ve emptied the canister, cut the film off and place the reel onto a spindle into the tank and lock the funnel into place. You can now turn the lights on.

Processing

Check that the temperature of the developer is 20°C. Set the timer for 15 seconds before the ascertained time and start it. Begin pouring the developer into the tank and close it with the lid within those 15 seconds. Slowly agitate the tank by tilting it upside down four times during the first 10 seconds. Repeat this every minute. As the timer nears zero, prepare to empty the developer down the drain. Once the tank is empty, empty the stop bath measuring cylinder into the tank and set the timer for 20 seconds and agitate the tank constantly. It doesn’t matter if you spend too long with this stage. Empty the stop bath back into the measuring cylinder. Now that the stop bath has been done; set the timer for 6 minutes, perhaps more if you are using recycled fixer. Agitate the tank as you did for the developer stage. Pour the fixer back into the measuring cylinder. It's a good idea to check your film has been fixed at this stage. Take the reel out of the tank and without unrolling the film check carefully if the film looks transparent and is without a milky fogging. If you find it has not been fixed properly just place back in the tank and refix for an extra 5 mins.

Finishing

To wash the film, fill the tank, agitate for 5 seconds then drain. Fill it again, agitate for 10 seconds then drain. Fill it yet again and agitate for 20 seconds then drain. Repeat this again. If you wish you can add a few drops of wetting agent at this stage. Do not drain the tank. Prepare the film clips and your choice of method to wipe the film. Tank your film out of the tank and wipe, either with a chamois cloth, a squeegee or your fingers. If you’re using a cloth or squeegee, dip it in the water and wetting agent solution left in the tank. You’re done! To dry the film, hang it in the drying cabinet with a heavy clip on the bottom and a light one on the top. You can leave the film dryer off and leave the film overnight to naturally dry, or you can use a low temperature to dry to film in half an hour, although it does tend to curl film.

Disposal

Pour the fixer back into the bottle. Do not pour fixer down the drain. If you wish to discard your solution, pour it into the ‘Waste Fixer’ bottle. Pour the stop bath back into the bottle if it is still yellow. If it has turned purple, then pour it down the drain. Created by James Mardell and updated by Sam Whitcomb

item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
HP5+ “The all rounder.” 400 speed general purpose film which has been labelled as bulletproof film! It is hard to develop wrong, it can be used in all sorts of lighting conditions and the exposure latitude is huge (it can be underexposed or overexposed by up to 3 stops). This film is perfect if you are new to photography and would like good results with nice fine grain.

Camera Guide Tutorials

Guide to Buying Cameras

How many different kinds of cameras are there? Which is the best camera for my budget? Where is the best place to get cameras? You'll find the answers to these questions and more on this tutorial.
Dates:
  • Wednesday 24th (3 to 4pm) - Huxley 130

Introduction to Camera Settings

What is exposure? How does the camera work to take a picture? How can I make the background of a photo blur naturally? In this tutorial we aim to give you the general idea of photography to help you on your photographic journey.
Dates:
  • Wednesday 24th (4 to 5pm) - Huxley 130

Studio shooting - Portrait & Fashion

item.title: Ilford Delta 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Professional 100 speed film which excels in fine grain control. The outdoor results are a pleasure to behold, as are the extraordinary sharpness and tonal smoothness. This film is perfect for those shooting outdoor, portraiture where smooth delicate tones are required although try not to push this film (don’t shoot at above 100 speed)!

Examples:

[zoom_picture id="1315"] [zoom_picture id="1320"]

item.title: Rollei Retro 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Rollei Retro “Cheap but reliable.” This film offers excellent value for money, and currently is our cheapest film. Apparently the film has excellent fog penetration, although from my own experience the main draws are its reliability and price. The 100 speed variant is reasonably smooth, although make sure you get the exposure roughly right!
[zoom_picture id="1329"]

item.title: Fuji Neopan 1600
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fuji Neopan 1600 “Classic grain structure!” Perfect for low light outdoor or indoor photography and offers the most beautiful grain structure. The film can be pushed to ISO3200 and is therefore essential for night shoots without a flash. The main draw is the sensational grain which creates a caustic, speckled texture which is a pleasure to the eye.
<!-- [zoom_picture id="1340"] [/zoom_picture] -->
[zoom_picture id="1545"] [/zoom_picture]
[zoom_picture id="1541"]Pushed to 3200 with Fomadon Excel (fine grain developer)[/zoom_picture]
[zoom_picture id="1658"]Shot at 1600 with Kodak T max developer[/zoom_picture]

item.title: FomaPan 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fomapan “historic film” comes in 100 and 400 speed. Uses a traditional emulsion from as early as the 1930’s and produces an old school black and white feel. This film isn’t as reliable as Kodak or Ilford, but the appeal comes from the want to shoot black and white in the traditional old school way. Even at 100 speed this film can look pretty grainy (comparable to T-Max).
[zoom_picture id="1346"]
[zoom_picture id="1347"]

item.title: Kodak Tri-X 400
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
TriX “Photojournalists choice” unchanged since the 50’s, this 400 speed film is one of the most versatile black and white films. Perfect for documentary, journalism, and street photography, this film has taken some of the most enduring images of the 20th century. This film has a pleasant grain, and is renowned as the most famous film in the world.
[zoom_picture id="1776"] [/zoom_picture]
[zoom_picture id="1547"] [/zoom_picture]
[zoom_picture id="1548"]Developed in Ilfotec HC [/zoom_picture]

item.title: Adox Art 50
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded: CHS Art 50 “Finest grain, beautiful prints” This film excels in producing exceptionally fine grain, and tonal separation. The emulsion unchanged from the 50’s gives a nostalgic feel and the prints that await will be stunning. This film is a little tricky to process being delicate when wet and the slow speed means it’s only suitable for flash, studio and bright outdoor photography.

item.title: Fuji Reala
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fuji Reala 100 is great for reproducing skin tones accurately. Colours are slightly more pastel like and rather subtle, but the effect is perfect for floral subjects and portraiture. Grain is minimal, a really robust film, although being 100 speed it is recommended that you use this outside.
[zoom_picture id="1372"]
[zoom_picture id="1371"]

item.title: Kodak Ektar 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Kodak Ektar is a 100 speed saturated colour negative film. Using the same emulsion technology as the films used in motion pictures, Ektar offers the smoothest grain of any colour negative. Some say it is a great alternative to shooting in slide film due to its extraordinary vivid colours, extreme smoothness, and scanning capabilities. Best suited to outdoor shooting, particularly on clear days.
[zoom_picture id="1779"] [/zoom_picture] [zoom_picture id="1380"]

item.title: Fomapan 400
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fomapan 400 film is nice alternative to the more well known films such as Tri-x and hp5. It doesn't claim amazing quality, but this is a result of it being produced in the way of traditional emulsions. Great for learning the art of photography, and at a reasonable price.
[zoom_picture id="1387"]

item.title: Ilford Delta 3200
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Ilford Delta 3200 is the highest speed film in its range. Slightly pricey, the 3200 lets you take photos with remarkable highlight detail in places that would be impossible without a flash. Some photographers claim to have pushed the film to ISO 25000 which may produce some serious grain, but at lower speeds the grain is very pleasant, and can add romanticism to your photos.
[zoom_picture id="1594"]
[zoom_picture id="1597"]

item.title: Fuji Velvia 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Velvia 100 is the faster variant of its world famous ‘little brother’ the Velvia 50. One of the most famous colour films ever produced, Velvia has enabled wildlife and landscape photographers to get those truly breathtaking shots in vivid colour. If colour is your thing, you MUST shoot a roll of Velvia, there really isn’t anything quite like it! Shooting in slide brings some technical hinderances: You must be very careful with your exposure, the latitude isn’t wide; also developing slide film is fine when we have chemicals in, but otherwise it can get pricy.
[zoom_picture id="1387"]

item.title: Fuji Sensia 100
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fuji Sensia 100 is a slide film all rounder. Ideal for wildlife, landscapes, portraits, it’s not quite as stunning as Velvia, but it still retains vivid colour, and detail but for a much lower price. Perfect for those wanting an affordable batch of slides, or those wanting to cross process some film (remember to check that the chemicals are at the right stage of use though!)
[zoom_picture id="1387"] Example photo coming soon...

item.title: Fuji Pro 400H
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Fujicolor pro 400H is a muted film delivering accurate skin tones with exceptional smoothness (film uses Fuji’s ‘most highly professional colour emulsion’). But the big advantage is its high speed: At ISO400 you will be able to shoot in a wide range of situations.
[zoom_picture id="1551"] [/zoom_picture]

item.title: Rule of Thirds
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
[caption id="attachment_1451" align="aligncenter" width="500" caption="Rule of Thirds Example"][/caption] Perhaps the most well known principle of photographic composition is the “Rule of Thirds”. It is one of the most basic tools that can be used to create balanced and visually appealing shots. However before we get into it I must warn you that rules are meant to be broken and ignoring this one doesn’t mean that your pictures will necessarily be unbalanced or uninteresting. In fact, the opposite can often be true!

What is the Rule of Thirds?

Put very simply, the basic principle is to break an image down into thirds both horizontally and vertically (as seen in the picture) so that you have 9 parts. Now keeping this grid in mind, the “rule of thirds” gives you four lines – two horizontal and two vertical - that can be used to help you compose your shot. Try positioning the points of interest in your picture either along one of the lines or at the intersections. Quick tip: some digital cameras can overlay the rule of thirds grid on top of the viewfinder to make this a lot easier so have a look around in the menu to see if you can find it. The theory is that by placing the points of interest in accordance with the “rule of thirds”, your picture will look more visually balanced and it will be easier for the viewer to focus on the object of interest. Studies have shown that when viewing an image, people’s eyes usually go to one of the intersection points more naturally than to the centre of the photograph; so using the ‘rule of thirds’ your picture will work with the viewer rather than against them. [caption id="attachment_1444" align="aligncenter" width="500" caption="I will let you overlay the “rule of thirds” grid yourself to this one!"][/caption] Applying the “Rule of Thirds” to your photography comes naturally to some photographers but it can take a little practice for it to become second nature. Once again, remember that breaking the rule can result in some striking shots too so once you’ve learnt it, experiment with purposely breaking it to see what you discover. Finally, keep the rule of thirds in mind as you edit your photos subsequently. Photo editing tools today have good tools for cropping and reframing images so that they fit better with the rule. Experiment with some of your old pictures to see what impact it has. Photographs by Jonathan Kim

item.title: Photosoc Exhibition 2011
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
It's exhibition time again! Every year Photosoc holds an exhibition in the Blyth Gallery in which members contribute the photographs. So we are asking you, our lovely members, to submit some beautiful images so that we can print them out and hang them for all to see! The theme this year is: “Reflection Through the Aperture” Have a good long think about what the theme means to you and how you can represent it in photographic form. We would prefer if you could take new images specifically for the theme rather than just trawl through your archive and to that end we will be holding some events next term based around the theme. Also the Christmas break is always a good opportunity to go out (no matter how cold it is!) and flex those photographic muscles. If you need some more inspiration then here is a list of suggestions:
  • Reflection on mirror, water or any other shiny surfaces;
  • Historical reflection
  • Emotional reflection
  • Thoughts, self-reflection
  • Others (use your imagination!)
To submit your photographs please email them to exhibition@icphotosoc.co.uk, including a title and a brief description of no more than 50 words each. The deadline for submissions is the 10th January 2011. We would love to exhibit all of your images however we only have limited space so a select group members will judge which pictures get selected for the final exhibition. If you want to find out more or have a look at pictures from last year's exhibition, head on over to the exhibition page.

item.title: Manifesto's for next years committee
item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Thanks to everyone who has already handed in their manifestos! We have decided to extend the deadline for any more to Monday midnight. There are still two positions that haven't been filled yet, the secretary and web manager, so just send your manifesto to photosoc@ic.ac.uk. The AGM will take place on Wed 16th March at 1-5pm in Union Building Activity Space 2 (Level 1). There will be free refreshments and lots of good company! So here are the current manifestos for PhotoSoc AGM 2010-11. If you think you can do better than just email us with your manifesto by Monday night.

PRESIDENT

Victor Cheng Hello all, I am Victor Cheng and I am studying BEng Computing (Year 1), running for the position of President/Chairman. If elected, I will strive for my very best to ensure PhotoSoc will run smoothly. I do believe I have the required vision and ideas on promoting PhotoSoc to make it a better and bigger society. Having been the President of the Hong Kong Joint School Photographic Society, I am experienced in resource management. I shouldered the responsibility of developing and fostering photography ethics among teenagers. The role put my leadership skills into test as I organized talks and oversaw events involving over 300 participants. I was subsequently invited to be a photographer at the Beijing Olympics 2008 and Famine30 after holding a press conference on photography and moral fibre. These opportunities provided me with a new set of lens through which I see the world from a different perspective, and I believe I will be able to excel as a chairman of PhotoSoc with all the experience gained and skills learnt during that time. I am extremely passionate about photography and I am sure next year will yet be another exciting and fruitful year for PhotoSoc. I will be look forward to rising up to the challenges PhotoSoc has in store for me.

VICE PRESIDENT

Slobodan I am standing for re-election as Vice-Chair of PhotoSoc after a year where much has been achieved. This has been one of the most eventful years for photosoc as far as long-term changes go. For a start, we have seen the darkroom being refurbished, with added storage and the new 'digital corner' and mini library. In effect, this makes the space much tidier (yes, I know, but you should have seen it before!) and more comfortable to use. Another difference to previous years is the introduction of a much more flexible equipment lending scheme. We are still exploring avenues to find someone who will meet our unique insurance needs, but for now we are lending out our stuff much more freely than before. Finally, it should be added that this year we received a MASSIVE financial boost from the Harlington Trust, allowing us to purchase a new camera kit that is unrivalled anywhere else in the UK. Looking ahead to the next year, how I would define this role (in addition to assisting the Chair when required) is one where you take the initiative to do all the little (and sometimes big) bits and bobs that need doing, be it designing posters, buying or replacing whatever needs it (batteries and light bulbs), chasing up new means of funding, for instance corporate sponsorship, writing various Health & Safety proposals for projects that haven't been tried before, or even dreaming up new gadgets and making them for the society, or showing people how to make them for themselves. I hope you'll all elect me to be the one to do this.

TREASURER

Charles Poon About my background, I am studying Mathematics and Computer Science in Year 2 with an entrance scholarship. Mathematics and computer science are both subjects which needs absolute correctness and attention to every details. In contrast, the treasurer's job is to understand all the club finances, and to make sure the society's budget is kept in good shape, with attention to every details. I have been around PhotoSoc for 2 years, and I do think I have already got enough knowledge to be a good treasurer. About photography, thanks to Alan Liu who inspired me into the world of photography 6 years ago, after 6 years of intensive photo-taking, I am a rather experienced photographer, attended quite a few professional seminars including a professional wedding workshop which I have attended on Feburary, I hope to hold some workshops about wedding photography and creative lighting during next year's Tutorial Weeks, hopefully with some professional models, if our members are willing to share the costs. Also, I will be working onto getting LRPS this summer, if I am successful, I will definitely hold a workshop guiding other members to getting similar world-renowned awards. Furthermore, as a treasurer, I would like to assist all the other committees to organise various activities to make a better PhotoSoc, as I have quite a lot of ideas of how to make a better PhotoSoc, which I failed to make it real this year. For example, Alan Liu suggested that we need a team of photographers who takes photos , I tried to implement the idea but it was too late and not many members showed their interest. I will assist the events coordinator next year to round this dream. At last, thanks for reading all these, and please vote for me, Charles Poon, for a better PhotoSoc!

SECRETARY

Position Open

DARKROOM MANAGER

Cheng Lao I first got involved with Photosoc at the beginning of my second year, having spent my first year meaning to get involved but not quite getting there. Since then I’ve been pretty pro-active, developing a load of rolls, doing a bit of printing and generally learning a ton of stuff about darkrooms, chemicals and film photography in general. I decided to run for Darkroom manager partly because I’m in the darkroom quite frequently and want to see the darkroom is still well run next year. But also I’d love to help out with the darkroom tutorials aspect of the position (which I think are a great thing) and get more people interested in film in general. I know that one of the many reasons I got interested in film was having a really good first film developing tutorial from an enthusiastic darkroom manager. Also as darkroom manager I’ll be able to continue the work on alternative printing and developing processes that Sam has introduced this year. Anyway to conclude, I’m confident with a little extra knowledge from the Photosoc team, I’ll be up to the job of running the Darkroom next year.

EVENTS COORDINATOR

Alan Liu Hello! My name is Alan. I am a 2nd year Medic and I am running for the events coordinator for the PhotoSoc. Just a little bit about my photographic experience – I got my first camera when I was 12 and have been a photographer (in schools and university) for about 7 years. I have covered a wide variety of events such as sports, concerts, plays, dinners, musical theatres, etc. and my photographs have been credited in various local newspapers, prospectus and websites (and Facebook albums, PhotoSoc exhibiton!) Currently, I am the head of the PhotoSoc’s Exhibition Committee, the Photographic Editior of the Gazette (ICSM magazine) and photographer for the medicalstudent Newspaper. The reason I want to run for this position is that I believe I could make a real difference to the way how it is working at the moment. Photographs are essential elements for publications and websites. At Imperial, opportunities for photographers are everywhere. There are hundreds of events happening every month and media loves photo coverage for most of them. In order to make this work, I would be willing to actively approach various publications to get “jobs” for photographers. Also, a central database/ spreadsheet will be provided for photographers to look up and sign up for photo coverage. Communication is very important among photographers and I think a monthly meeting should be held to exchange ideas and build rapports. I will also be willing to share my experience and give training to photographers when necessary. At last, thank you very much for reading! If you are interested in my proposals and would like to see changes happening for the PhotoSoc next year, please support and vote for me as the events coordinator!

SOCIAL SECRETARY

David Zheng My name is David Zheng, the vice chair of Photosoc exhibition committee this year. I am applying for the social secretary, based on the socializing and negotiating skills gained from fundraising £16000 in high schools in China and America. Through working on the exhibition committee, I have some ideas to make our society better.
  • Initiating a sub-committee mainly contains passionate, enthusiastic 1st year students
  • A team to assist committee, divide up jobs, share the loads, collect diversity of ideas, variety of suggestions;
  • They can gain communication, teamwork, leadership skills;
  • Organizing an online based exhibition for events photography
  • Applying the sponsorship
  • By Canon, Nikon, so that we can get technical and equipment supports;
  • By Silverprint, so that we may have more discount or prizes for exhibitions;
  • Holding combined events and trips with LSE and UCL Photosoc
  • Since all London school, we should have more co-operations;
  • Share the diversities, either learn from them or give them helps all determined to make us better;
  • Having more one-day trips
  • To try my best and get the permission from Union;
  • Make the trips more interesting
  • Open a facebook group or public album just for members
  • Members could show off their galleries and share opinions about photography;
  • Made by Photosoc ---- Sales of photo by-products
  • Including calendars, postcards, order prints, and…… even to art galleries;
  • Arrange more social events like parties and dinner
I have more ideas about making Photosoc better; please vote for me, David Zheng as the Social Secretary. Thank you. Eliie Sansom Next year will be busy Busy BUSY! There are probably those that don't know me because I ran away this year to study in California, but no worries! I’ll be back and ready next year with some very exciting ideas! I’m super enthusiastic about photography and want to try new things and learn new things. I want to organise bi-weekly get-togethers (as well as photo walks) where we can experiment and be more creative with out cameras and photos. Photo walks are awesome for going and being snap-happy and getting some great advise and inspiration from others (without feeling too much like a tourist in London!) but there are many many other cool things you can do with a camera! Ever tried making fun shaped Bokeh? Light painting with glow sticks? Been the photographer in a photo shoot? We could also make photo walks into photo safaris! Pick a random adjective such as orange or shiny and see what we come up with! I also think that the exposition every year is great for showing off photos that others’ rarely see but why not share a photo or two during meetings. Facebook is fine and good for all those photo walk pictures from last week, but why not pick your favourite and hear what others’ have to say? Could your lighting have been better? What great contrast! What shutter speed did you use? A time to share some constructive criticism and maybe you’ll start looking for that little extra next time you take a photo! I can’t wait to be back for another year of Photosoc and I hope you’ll let me make it its most exciting yet!

EQUIPMENTS MANAGER

Ka Ho Tam My name is Ka Ho and I will be standing for the position of Equipments Manager in the 2011/12 Committee. I am a third year physicist at Imperial College. I had become enthusiastic about photography since I got my first DSLR 6 years ago, and had been taking photos in both my spare time and in my high school's photography team as the team captain. This year I joined PhotoSoc and had a great time with all the trips and events, so now I wish to contribute to the society. I believe I am suitable for the position I am applying for as I have good knowledge on photographic equipments and also got an interest in optics (yes, welcome to Imperial). I will be able to answer a wide range of questions, and would love to transfer different photographic skills and techniques to our new members in the tutorial weeks! I'd be able to cover many relevant topics in depth from exposure to DIY equipments. This will be an important mission of PhotoSoc as digital photography becomes more affordable and an increasing number of novice members join in. If I am elected I would prioritise my time on the society and our members. I will be readily reachable for your needs, and produce a clear list of equipments for our society to ensure fair and responsible usage from everyone. (Like many others I own a number of lenses and a bag of accessories and had learned to be very careful with them.) Apart from that I also wish to work with other members as a team to cover trips and events to ensure the society runs smoothly. PhotoSoc had been extremely rewarding and we will need people to ensure that the club continues its mighty expansion.

WEB MANAGER

Position Open

item.dc:creator: jkimbo
item.content:encoded:
Chair Re-Election

At the end of last term we voted in a fantastic new committee to drive the society forward next year. However the position of Chair has not been decided on as yet and so we have now re-opened the position to all members. This is a brilliant chance to lead a group of passionate individuals like you! As a past chair I can tell you there is a lot of commitment in taking up this role but it is a highly rewarding position that gives you an opportunity to make a difference. Please send us your manifesto to photosoc@imperial.ac.uk by the 1st of May (midnight) and if you have any questions feel free to contact us. All manifestos will then be posted online before the online voting, which will take place between the 4th of May and the 11th. Jonathan Kim

End of Spring Term and Plans

Spring term has now come to an end, and we are taking a break from our regular activities to finish up revision for exams! There will no activities including Thursday meetings, until late May. However we will try and be prompt with emails as usual, and a couple of us may be around during Easter to help with any queries you may have. Hopefully we will again be able to organise some more tutorials (this time will be about lighting skills!) and photo walks (such as the famed London 4am trip), after the 20th of May, but until then good luck to all revision plans and see you after exams! :) Charles Poon

Canon Kit

We are in the process of writing a report/thank-you to the people who gave us the money to buy our most recent Canon kit. As such, it would be really useful if those of you who have been borrowing and using the 5D mk2 or any of the new lenses could send in any particularly impressive pictures you've taken. We love seeing what you're up to, and I'm sure the Harlington committee will too. When you email us, can you make sure the image exif stays intact !

Phoenix

Hello keen photographers! Some of you may already have heard of Phoenix; the annual arts magazine of Imperial College. In essence, Phoenix is just a vehicle for the artistic output of the college. It will be published in June this year, taking the place of Felix for one week; as such it's a really great way to have your work reach a wide audience. Over here we're particularly enthusiastic to have some photography featured (particularly since the entries so far have been fairly word-heavy). So if you've got pieces that you'd like to see published, no matter how many or how few, send them in to: phoenix@imperial.ac.uk. (Deadline is 1st May.) Also you can find our Facebook page here: http://www.facebook.com/pages/Phoenix/170568019924 Thanks! Navid Nabijou (Phoenix co-editor)

item.title: Medium Format or 35mm?
item.dc:creator: syw07
item.content:encoded:
The camera bug is easy to catch, especially in the world of film where classic cameras can be picked up for next to nothing. I admit initially I was infected, but despite buying 7 cameras and throwing 2 away, I’m pleased to report I’m over the worst of it! It was relatively early into my camera fest that I considered buying a medium format camera motivated by their ability to take big square photos, use cool old school fat film, and also joining the fraternity of medium format shooters at Imperial! This article will hopefully tell you enough about medium format to join in on any of our ‘square’ conversations in the Thursday meet-ups and help anyone who’s debating dropping some dough on one of these bad boys. So, for those not in the know, medium format refers to the format of the film. We have 3 main sizes of photographic film available:

35mm film which has become the standard size for shooting - 35mm wide including its perforated edge producing photos 24x36mm 120 format (medium format) which takes photos 6cm wide, square or rectangular Large format is anything above 6x9cm and is sold as single shot sheets of film.

Now a lot of articles will say that medium format is for the more serious photographer shooting studio work, commercial outdoor work, and for those who require bigger prints. After all, the cameras are often more difficult to operate, heavier to cart around, and can be much more expensive. Personally I say pish to all that; the draw of the camera is the feel of the photos it creates, as well as the novelty.

How do they feel?

My experience has been with the twin lens reflex camera (TLR depicted above). I saw another member fumbling with a queer double lensed box and I immediately fell in love with the beautiful way you view the image not through a viewfinder but down on a plate at waist level where you can see the image framed as if it were a 3D print. You carefully load the film in a fiddly old fashioned routine involving transferring spools and threading paper; you view the photo to be, and really concentrate on composition. Finally you consider lighting, and remember that through the viewfinder everything looks back to front and take care to select the correct shutter speed and aperture. Wow this is becoming complicated, but all this drama and care ensures that you and your photo are committed together and because you only get 12 shots per roll, you really savour this routine with your beloved box. Developing is a little trickier due to the films tendency to curl and the lack of a perforated edge; however the method is the same. But you must let the results speak for themselves; these big negatives allow a greater dynamic range (that is difference between whites and blacks) and cause the grain to appear smaller, smoother and seem to emit a quality as a result. Some of the older models also allow a function which I’ve grown to love and hate – double exposure! If you forget to wind your camera after a shot you end up taking a photo one atop the other, a rather interesting, confusing technique which can produce stunning shots.

Jonathan Kim using TLR (Yashica-mat)
Chris Walmsely - multiple exposure using folding camera (Zeiss Ikon Nettar)
Sam Whitcomb using TLR (Ricohflex Dia)
Is 120 for you?

I say shooting medium format can be vastly different from shooting 35mm. Different aspect ratios, particularly the square, enable different compositions which can be reminiscent of the Polaroid, unusual, casual, simplistic and in my opinion slightly more nostalgic than the 6:9 of the 35mm. Furthermore, shooting from the waist gives a completely different perspective on the action, and can allow a more natural response due to the camera being out of the subjects face. 35mm is certainly more convenient, quick, discreet; you certainly don’t get as many stares, and you get 36 shots – ideal for the travelling photographer, or quick snaps on the street or at a party. For the photographer who loves the act of taking a photo, and is naturally more reserved with the shutter (after all it is quality not quantity that counts) medium format is a must! The cameras can be more basic and so demand a little more patience, for example a lot of medium format camera don’t have a light meter and therefore a handheld light meter can be pretty useful, but don’t be put off – it doesn’t take long to get a feel for it, and shooting full manual is a great way to learn the ins and outs of photography.

Are these things cheap?

Medium format cameras come in many shapes and sizes, the twin lens which I describe above, SLR’s, rangefinders, and the older folding types which are completely portable and can offer incredibly sharp optics, or lomo type lightleaks, either way you probably won’t have to ask your subjects to smile! A good consumer camera will cost from around £40 to £150, my box cost me £50 (Ricohflex Dia), Holga’s and Diana’s for the lomo lovers will put you out around £25. The film itself is slightly cheaper than its 35mm counterpart, but considering the area of film is roughly the same it works out fairly at around £2.50-£3.50 per roll.

For anyone who wishes to try the format, Photosoc have an excellent twin lens reflex, and 2 amazing medium format SLRs available to borrow. Feel free to come to the weekly Photosoc meetings to learn more.
